{"_id":"942b1610-bc62-11ea-bd69-452e7adaa71f","postId":"2017_03_aspnetcore-synchronization-context-ad62260e-a3f5-3648-b8e3-575b9b12f379","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2017/03/aspnetcore-synchronization-context.html","replyTo":"608620f0-bc50-11ea-88c7-21f68a349301","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"The general rule that I follow is to use `ConfigureAwait(false)` in any general-purpose library. So if your library can be used by ASP.NET pre-Core, or by GUI apps, then I would recommend `ConfigureAwait(false)`.\r\n\r\nHowever, not everyone agrees with that rule. There's a decent counterargument that recommends not using `ConfigureAwait(false)` anywhere at all, and that it's up to the consumer to call it correctly.","date":"2020-07-02T12:50:16.899Z"}